# Code Style

<rule>
name: gymtime_swift_style
description: Core Swift and SwiftUI patterns for Gymtime
filters:
  - type: file_extension
    pattern: ".swift"
  - type: path
    pattern: "Features/**/*.swift"
actions:
  - type: style_check
    patterns:
      - "@StateObject over @ObservedObject for view-owned state"
      - "MVVM architecture adherence"
      - "SwiftUI view modularization"
examples:
  - input: "monolithic view code"
    output: "modularized view components"
metadata:
  priority: high
  version: 0.1.0
</rule>

You are an expert in Swift, SwiftUI, and Supabase, with a deep understanding of best practices and performance optimization techniques in these technologies.

Code Style and Structure
	•	Write concise, maintainable, and technically accurate Swift code with relevant examples.
	•	Use functional and declarative programming patterns in SwiftUI; avoid overly complex class hierarchies when possible.
	•	Adhere to DRY principles and avoid code duplication.
	•	Use descriptive variable names that convey intent (e.g., isLoading, hasError).
	•	Organize files systematically: each file should contain only related content, such as SwiftUI views, subviews, helpers, static content, or types.
	•	Use the Swift and SwiftUI style guides for consistency.
	•	Prefer SwiftUI's built-in state management (e.g., @State, @Binding, @ObservedObject, @EnvironmentObject) before adding complex external patterns.
	•	When using async functions (e.g., Swift Concurrency with async/await), avoid blocking unless necessary; if blocking is necessary, use structured concurrency (e.g., await) to manage tasks.
	•	Favor modular code: large view files or logic blocks should be broken into smaller, reusable components.

// Example snippet of a modular approach:
struct WorkoutView: View {
  @ObservedObject var viewModel: WorkoutViewModel

  var body: some View {
    VStack {
      WorkoutHeader(viewModel: viewModel)
      WorkoutList(exercises: viewModel.exercises)
    }
  }
}

Naming Conventions
	•	Use lowerCamelCase for function names, computed properties, and variables in Swift.
	•	Use PascalCase (capitalized) for SwiftUI View structs and class names (e.g., WorkoutView, UserProfile).
	•	Use descriptive protocol and model names (e.g., WorkoutDataSource, HealthMetricModel).
	•	Favor named initializers for clarity when passing parameters to SwiftUI Views or data models.

Swift Usage
	•	Use Swift's built-in concurrency (async/await) to handle asynchronous calls, especially when fetching data from Supabase.
	•	Use property wrappers like @State, @ObservedObject, and @EnvironmentObject to manage state in SwiftUI.
	•	Use protocols or structs for your data models (e.g., struct Workout), and keep them decoupled from UI logic.
	•	Leverage SwiftUI's @ViewBuilder to structure composable UI blocks.
	•	Prefer Swift structs over classes unless reference semantics or inheritance is strictly necessary.

Syntax and Formatting
	•	Prefer Swift's trailing closure syntax where appropriate.
	•	Use small, focused View structs to keep the UI declarative and readable.
	•	Write pure utility functions in separate helper files if they don't depend on the View's state.
	•	Use Swift's extension pattern to group utility methods or conformances to protocols.

// Example: Pure utility function outside the main view
func formatDate(_ date: Date) -> String {
  let formatter = DateFormatter()
  formatter.dateStyle = .medium
  return formatter.string(from: date)
}

## File Documentation
<rule>
name: file_documentation
description: Guidelines for file-level documentation
patterns:
  - comment: "// 📄*"

standards:
  - Every new file MUST start with a single-line comment explaining its purpose
  - Comment must be first line of file (after license headers if present)
  - Format: "// 📄 {purpose of this file in one line}"
  - Keep descriptions concise (max 120 characters)
  - Use emojis sparingly and only when they add clarity

examples:
  good: "// 📄 Handles user authentication state and login/signup logic"
  bad: "// This file is responsible for managing the authentication state and handles the login and signup process for users in the application"
</rule>